04021nam a22005295i 9780804777599DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202011cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047775997 a10.1515/97808047775992doi  a(DE-B1597)564173  a(OCoLC)1178770073  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHV6791 .A585 2011 7aBUS0440002bisacsh04a364.9731 aAllen, W. David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCriminals and Victims /cW. David Allen. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Who Are Criminals? A Review -- t2. The Planning of Crime -- t3. Violence and Damages -- t4. The Destruction of Evidence -- t5. The Recommission of Crime: Recidivism -- t6. Who Are Victims? A Review -- t7. Self- Protection Against Crime Victimization -- t8. The Decision to Resist -- t9. The Decision to Report -- t10. Labor- Market Consequences of Crime Victimization -- tEpilogue -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCriminals and Victims presents an economic analysis of decisions made by criminals and victims of crime before, during, and after a crime or victimization occurs. Its main purpose is to illustrate how the application of analytical tools from economics can help us to understand the causes and consequences of criminal and victim choices, aiding efforts to deter or reduce the consequences of crime. By examining these decisions along a logical timeline over which crimes take place, we can begin to think more clearly about how policy effects change when it is targeted at specific decisions within the body of a crime. This book differs from others by recognizing the timeline of a crime, paying particular attention to victim decisions, and examining each step in the crime cycle at the micro-level. It demonstrates that criminals plan their crimes in systematic, economically logical ways; that deterring the destruction of criminal evidence may deter crime in general; and that white-collar criminals exhibit recidivism patterns not unlike those of street criminals. It further shows that the degree of criminality in a society motivates a variety of self-protection behaviors by potential victims; that not all victim resistance makes matters worse (and some may help); and that victims who report their crimes do not receive high returns for going to the police, helping to explain why some crimes ultimately go unreported.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCrimexEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aCriminal behaviorxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aCriminalszUnited States. 0aVictims of crimeszUnited States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / Microeconomics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804777599zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804777599423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804777599.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles